{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f9be4865-70c5-403b-a83f-1d48fc23c9d6","content":"You can install `dotnet-trace` as a standalone tool without the SDK:\n\n```bash\n# From inside the container, download and install as a global tool\ncurl -sSL https://dot.net/v1/dotnet-install.sh | bash /dev/stdin --runtime dotnet --version 8.0.0\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.dotnet:$PATH\"\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.dotnet/tools:$PATH\"\n```\n\nOr, **faster** — grab the standalone single-file build directly:\n\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o /tmp/dotnet-trace\nchmod +x /tmp/dotnet-trace\n```\n\nThen collect a CPU trace:\n\n```bash\n# Find your app's PID\nps aux | grep dotnet\n\n# Collect a CPU profile (default provider includes CPU sampling)\n/tmp/dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can copy out (`docker cp`) and analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`dotnet-trace convert --format speedscope`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5b7ccd7d-57b5-4058-92d6-5d57e0c25646","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a knowledge question — I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":390,"requestId":"D81A:36DBF5:211A77F:24B58E7:6A03D4D3"},"id":"98084e8c-98e2-4b37-b5a5-ab2f7f7565f0","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:33:16.688Z","parentId":"c6d3c426-1fe8-4ba7-850f-667eabcaae73"}
